<div class="info-section">
    <h3>Understanding CO<sub>2</sub> Levels</h3>
    <p>
        The video displays monthly gridded retrievals of Carbon Dioxide in the free troposphere from January 2010 to February 2017. 
        The data is sourced from the AIRS instrument aboard the Aqua satellite and illustrates how CO<sub>2</sub> levels have fluctuated over time.
    </p>
    <p>
        The gradient image above shows CO<sub>2</sub> concentrations ranging from <strong>&lt; 390 ppmv</strong> (parts per million by volume) to <strong>&gt; 405 ppmv</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Over the years, the increase in CO<sub>2</sub> levels has worsened, highlighting the urgent need for change in our environmental practices and policies. 
        Addressing climate change is crucial for the sustainability of our planet.
    </p>
    <p>
        For more information on the AIRS instrument and its data products, visit <a href="https://airs.jpl.nasa.gov" target="_blank">AIRS Overview</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Explore an interactive map of CO<sub>2</sub> levels at <a href="https://worldview.earthdata.nasa.gov/" target="_blank">NASA Worldview</a>.
    </p>
